# Authentication

- Never store passwords in plain text; use bcrypt, argon2, or scrypt with per-user salt.
- Prefer established auth providers (OAuth2/OIDC, Auth0, Clerk) over custom auth when possible.
- Use short-lived access tokens + refresh tokens; rotate refresh tokens on use.
- Store sessions server-side or use signed JWTs with short expiry and secure httpOnly cookies.
- Validate tokens on every protected request; fail closed (401), never silently degrade.
- Implement MFA for sensitive operations and admin access.
- Rate-limit login and password reset endpoints against brute force.
- Never log passwords, tokens, or secrets.
- Use constant-time comparison for token/signature verification.
- Provide secure password reset with time-limited, single-use tokens.
